<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-03-14T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-03-14T18:00:00-05:00" n="758" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d758">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.711/17: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-14T18:00:00-05:00">March 14, 1929—6
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>95. Your 171, March 12, 5 p.m. Department approves attitude outlined in
                            paragraph 2 of your telegram. Please keep Department informed of further
                                developments.<note n="57" xml:id="d758fn57">The Minister in China,
                                in telegram No. 261, April 4, reported: “Following from Tientsin,
                                April 3, noon: Postal ban on the <hi rend="italic">North China
                                    Star</hi> lifted today” (893.711/26).</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>